          "body": "The chapter's central theological moment is the humbling in verses 6-7. The princes of Israel and the king hear Shemaiah's indictment and respond with a theologically precise confession: 'The LORD is righteous' (12:6). They do not argue the justice of the discipline, negotiate its terms, or appeal to prior covenant loyalty. They accept the verdict. This is kana — genuine submission to divine authority. God's response is immediate and instructive: 'They have humbled themselves so I will not destroy them, but I will grant them some measure of deliverance' (12:7). Three features of this response demand attention. First, it is responsive — God sees the humbling and acts on it; divine wrath is not mechanically predetermined. Second, it is proportional — 'some measure of deliverance,' not full rescue. The humbling was real but incomplete (as 12:14 will confirm), and God's mercy matches its depth. Third, it is pedagogical — they will become Shishak's slaves 'so that they may learn the difference between My service and the service of the kingdoms of the countries' (12:8). Discipline retained is discipline with purpose. The suffering that remains after partial mercy is not cruelty but curriculum."
