          "body": "The detail of the shields in verses 9-11 is one of the Chronicler's most subtle theological strokes. Solomon had made 300 large golden shields and 300 small ones (1 Kings 10:16-17; 2 Chronicles 9:15-16), displayed in the House of the Forest of Lebanon and carried in royal processions. They were the visible emblem of Solomon's God-given glory — tangible evidence that the covenant king's prosperity was divinely sourced. Shishak takes all of them (12:9). Rehoboam replaces them with bronze — cheaper, dimmer, a functional substitute for what was irreplaceable (12:10). The guards carry them out when the king enters the Temple and return them to the guardroom (12:11). The rhythm is now performance rather than possession: the symbols of glory must be fetched out and then secured again, because they no longer truly belong to the king. Calvin, commenting on the parallel passage, observed that God often permits us to retain the form of religion after we have lost its substance. The bronze shields are the chapter's most compact image of what forsaking costs: not annihilation but permanent diminishment, a life spent imitating in bronze what was once genuinely gold."
