        "body": "The opening verse of chapter 12 functions as the Chronicler's thesis statement for the entire reign. Its syntax is deliberately paradoxical: the 'when' clause places strength and establishment as the temporal and causal occasion for forsaking. This is not the desperate apostasy of a cornered people reaching for foreign gods under military pressure — it is the comfortable apostasy of a people who feel they no longer need the covenant relationship that produced their strength.\n\nThe Chronicler has set this up carefully. In chapter 11, Rehoboam had strengthened himself, built fortified cities, and received the priests and Levites driven from the north after Jeroboam's schism (2 Chronicles 11:5-17). For three years 'they walked in the way of David and Solomon' (11:17). The three-year fidelity was enough to produce the strength described in 12:1. Then came the forsaking. The Chronicler's point is structural: the covenant blessings of strength and establishment, received apart from continuing covenant fidelity, become the occasion of spiritual drift.\n\nThe phrase 'he and all Israel with him' (12:1) is significant. The Chronicler uses 'all Israel' in a characteristic way — the covenant community, north and south, is bound together in its representative king's posture. Rehoboam's forsaking is not a solo private failure; it is the failure of the whole covenant people insofar as the king represents them. This corporate solidarity is not merely political. In Deuteronomic and Chronicler theology, the king's covenant posture shapes the spiritual climate of the whole nation (cf. Deuteronomy 17:18-20, where the king's personal reading of the Torah is the mechanism by which the whole people are preserved from apostasy).\n\nThe specific object forsaken is 'the law of the LORD' (Torah Yahweh). This is not vague religious neglect but specific abandonment of the revealed covenant instruction. In the Chronicler's framework, the Torah is the instrument by which God's character and will are communicated to His people. To forsake it is to sever the primary channel of covenant relationship.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kun* (established) — to be firm, stable, prepared. The same root appears in verse 13 when Rehoboam 'strengthened himself' after the discipline — he returns to the same verb, suggesting a recovery of the establishment he had enjoyed before. *Azav* (forsook) — to leave, abandon, desert. Its repeated use in verse 5 ('you have forsaken Me... I have forsaken you') makes the lex talionis of the covenant explicit: abandonment produces abandonment."
