        "body": "Verses 2-5 move from the theological statement of verse 1 to its historical execution. The narrator gives the date (fifth year), the mechanism (Shishak's invasion), the scale (1,200 chariots, 60,000 horsemen, three named African peoples), and the geographic progress (fortified cities of Judah → Jerusalem). The scale is not hyperbolic for effect — Shishak's own victory inscription at the temple of Amun in Karnak lists over 150 Palestinian cities he claims to have taken in this campaign, which modern archaeology dates to approximately 925 BC. The Chronicler has compressed a significant military campaign into four verses, but the historical foundation is secure.\n\nThe critical move is Shemaiah's prophetic interpretation in verse 5. Without this verse, the invasion is merely a geopolitical event — a new Egyptian dynasty flexing its power in a period of Palestinian political instability following the division of Solomon's kingdom. With Shemaiah's word, the invasion becomes transparent: it is the form that divine forsaking takes in history. God does not typically act directly and miraculously to discipline covenant breakers; He removes the protection that held back the nations, and the nations fill the vacuum. This is the Deuteronomic pattern: covenant unfaithfulness results in the withdrawal of divine protection, which results in military vulnerability (Deuteronomy 28:25, 33, 48).\n\nThe form of Shemaiah's word is precise — 'Thus says the LORD' (*koh amar Yahweh*), the classic prophetic messenger formula that signals the prophet is delivering, not composing, the divine word. The content mirrors the action: 'You have forsaken Me (*azavtem*), so I also have forsaken you (*azavti*) to Shishak.' The covenant logic is exact — what you did to Me, I have done to you through Shishak. The invader is not acting independently; he is the instrument in the hand of the covenant God. Howard Hendricks's observation that narrative theology in the Old Testament is never merely descriptive but always evaluative applies precisely here: the Chronicler is not reporting events but interpreting them under the category of covenant faithfulness.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Maal* (unfaithful, v.2) — treachery against a covenant partner. The Chronicler uses it as a near-technical term for covenant violation: Saul died for his *maal* (1 Chronicles 10:13); Ahaz's *maal* brought the Assyrian crisis (2 Chronicles 28:19). Its appearance here categorizes Rehoboam's forsaking as the same species of offense. *Navi* (prophet) — the designated receptor and transmitter of divine word; Shemaiah's role is interpretive, not predictive."
