        "body": "The response of Rehoboam and the princes in verse 6 is theologically remarkable in its economy: 'The LORD is righteous.' It is the shortest complete response to prophetic indictment in the Chronicler's royal narratives. They do not argue, negotiate, or appeal. They accept the divine verdict as just. This is *kana* — bending the knee, submission to superior authority. The acknowledgment 'The LORD is righteous' (*tsaddiq Yahweh*) is not merely polite capitulation; it is a theological confession. It accepts that God's character — His righteousness — is the standard by which the discipline must be measured, and that the discipline does not exceed that standard. It is the same confession Ezra would later make on behalf of the post-exilic community (Ezra 9:15) and that the prophets would return to repeatedly (Lamentations 1:18; Daniel 9:14).\n\nGod's response is immediate (v.7). He does not delay, demand a certain number of days of repentance, or require further demonstration. He sees (*ra'ah*) the humbling and responds. This is the living, personally engaged God of the covenant — not a deistic administrator processing requests but a relational God who watches, responds, and calibrates. The mercy offered is graduated: 'some measure of deliverance' (*peletah me'at*) — a little escape, a partial rescue. The Hebrew *me'at* (a little, a small amount) is precise: God is not offering full restoration but proportional mercy, calibrated to the depth of the humbling.\n\nVerse 8 is the chapter's most provocative theological statement: they will become Shishak's slaves 'so that they may learn the difference between My service and the service of the kingdoms of the countries.' The word for 'service' (*avodah*) is the same in both cases — the difference is not the word but the object. Serving God and serving a foreign king both cost something. The lesson of subjugation to Shishak is that the burden of serving a foreign master is greater, less purposeful, and ultimately enslaving in a way that service to God is not. The comparison resonates canonically with the Exodus narrative: Israel in Egypt knew exactly what it meant to serve *both* Pharaoh and YHWH, and the entire Sinai covenant was framed as liberation from one avodah into another (Exodus 19:4-6). Rehoboam's generation needs to re-learn what their ancestors knew.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kana* (humbled themselves) — to bend, bow, bring low. Used in Chronicles as the technical term for the posture that activates divine mercy: see 2 Chronicles 7:14 ('if My people who are called by My name humble themselves'). *Peletah me'at* (some measure of deliverance, literally 'a small escape') — God calibrates mercy to the quality of the humbling. *Avodah* (service/slavery) — the same word in both clauses of v.8; the contrast is entirely in the object, not the term."
