        "body": "The chapter closes with the Chronicler's summary formula — regnal details (age at accession, length of reign, capital city, mother's name) followed by source citations and a moral verdict. The regnal details are not merely archival. 'The city which the LORD had chosen from all the tribes of Israel, to put His name there' (12:13) reminds the reader that Rehoboam's reign, despite its failures, remained within the orbit of God's covenant choice. The Davidic dynasty in Jerusalem persists not because Rehoboam deserves it but because God chose Jerusalem and put His name there. The dynasty's continuity is an act of divine faithfulness, not human merit.\n\nNaamah the Ammonitess (12:13) is one of Solomon's foreign wives (1 Kings 14:21, 31) — her national identity signals the compromised lineage from which Rehoboam came. She is from the same moral world that led Solomon astray (1 Kings 11:1-8). The Chronicler includes her name not as genealogical interest but as theological context: Rehoboam was born into a household already compromised by foreign religious influence.\n\nThe verdict in verse 14 is the sharpest single sentence in the chapter: 'He did evil because he did not set his heart to seek the LORD.' Two features are exegetically decisive. First, the causal 'because' (*ki*) makes seeking-God not merely an absent virtue but the identified root cause of his failure. Everything in the chapter — the forsaking, the crisis humbling, the bronze substitution, the ongoing evil — is traceable to this one failure of heart-orientation. Second, the verb is *darash* (to seek, to inquire of), and the modifier is *kun lev* (to set/prepare the heart). This is not merely the absence of seeking — it is the failure to *establish* seeking as the governing disposition of the inner life. Rehoboam could seek God reactively in a crisis (vv.6, 12); what he never did was make seeking God the settled orientation from which he operated in strength as well as in crisis.\n\nD. A. Carson's observation about the difference between occasional spiritual experience and a sustained orientation toward God is applicable here: Rehoboam is the Chronicler's exhibit of a king whose religion was entirely reactive and never became habitual. The post-exilic community rebuilding under Ezra and Nehemiah needed exactly this warning — the rebuilt Temple could generate the forms of worship without anyone in the congregation having set his heart to seek the LORD.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Darash* (to seek) — in Chronicles this verb is the diagnostic of covenant fidelity. Its presence or absence in a king's biography typically predicts the shape of his reign. *Kun lev* (set the heart, literally to prepare/establish the heart) — intentional alignment, not episodic response. The failure was dispositional, not behavioral: Rehoboam's problem was not merely that he did wrong things but that he never oriented his inner life toward God as the starting point."
